</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<taxonomicName authority="Frey, 1946" authorityName="Frey" authorityYear="1946" class="Insecta" family="Phytomyzinae" genus="Xenophytomyza" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Xenophytomyza" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Xenophytomyza</taxonomicName>
. Hering 1955: 170.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="note">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<taxonomicName authority="Frey, 1946" authorityName="Frey" authorityYear="1946" class="Insecta" family="Poaceae" genus="Xenophytomyza" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Xenophytomyza" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Xenophytomyza</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is primarily north temperate in distribution, with seven exclusively Palaearctic species (mostly Russian), one Holarctic and Jamaican species, and one eastern Nearctic species. The three species with known hosts have all been reared from 
<taxonomicName authority="Frey, 1946" authorityName="Frey" authorityYear="1946" class="Insecta" family="Poaceae" genus="Xenophytomyza" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Poaceae</taxonomicName>
(Boucher 2003).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
The single Delmarva species is distinct among other local 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Agromyzidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="? arthropoda" rank="family">Agromyzidae</taxonomicName>
in having three dorsocentrals that strongly decrease in length anteriorly, and there is a mix of characters seen in other 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Rondani" authorityYear="1861" class="Insecta" family="Phytomyzinae" genus="Cerodontha" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Cerodontha" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Cerodontha</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
subgenera: the lateral scutellar seta is absent (also seen in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Rondani" authorityYear="1861" class="Insecta" family="Phytomyzinae" genus="Cerodontha" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Cerodontha" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Cerodontha</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
s. s.), the first flagellomere has a strong anterodorsal angle (but not produced to a point as seen in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Rondani" authorityYear="1861" class="Insecta" family="Phytomyzinae" genus="Cerodontha" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Cerodontha" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Cerodontha</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
s. s.), the lunule is narrow and slightly higher than wide (similar to some 
<taxonomicName authority="Hendel, 1931" authorityName="Hendel" authorityYear="1931" class="Insecta" family="Poaceae" genus="Poemyza" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Poemyza" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Poemyza</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) and the body is darkly pigmented. Support for the subgenus is weak and its relationships to other subgenera require investigation (Boucher 2003).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
